1
00:00:03,031 --> 00:00:06,636
In Vienna, two maternity wards sat under one hospital roof.

2
00:00:07,397 --> 00:00:09,700
The First Clinic was run by doctors and students.

3
00:00:10,602 --> 00:00:12,144
The Second was run by midwives.

4
00:00:12,926 --> 00:00:14,087
The patients were similar.

5
00:00:14,868 --> 00:00:16,111
The death rates were not.

6
00:00:17,071 --> 00:00:22,440
By 1846, the First Clinic was losing more than one in ten mothers.

7
00:00:22,420 --> 00:00:25,984
Across the same years, the Second stayed under four percent.

8
00:00:26,846 --> 00:00:28,989
Semmelweis found the difference in the routine.

9
00:00:29,048 --> 00:00:34,998
Doctors moved from autopsies to childbirth without effective disinfection.

10
00:00:35,819 --> 00:00:38,442
He required chloride-of-lime hand disinfection.

11
00:00:39,463 --> 00:00:40,384
Mortality fell.

12
00:00:41,447 --> 00:00:44,390
The evidence worked before germ theory could explain why.

13
00:00:44,411 --> 00:00:46,774
That was the problem.

14
00:00:46,753 --> 00:00:51,594
Believing the data meant believing doctors had been carrying death from the dead to the living.

15
00:00:51,634 --> 00:00:56,253
The institution protected its identity longer than it protected the evidence.

16
00:00:57,078 --> 00:01:00,392
Small causes, massive consequences.
